@PennyQ @maxwelltsai - here is a simple implementation of the glue code to listen to subset additions/changes. At the moment this is not necessarily very efficient, but it should allow you now focus on the visualization.

To try this out (once merged), load a cube, then start up a 3D data viewer as well as a histogram viewer. Then, select a range in the histogram viewer. When you do this, ``QtVispyWidget.set_subsets`` will get called (you can add a print statement there to check if you like) and will be given a list of dictionaries. Each dictionary contains ``'mask'``, which is a boolean mask that is the same size/shape as the data, and indicates which pixels are selected, and the color and alpha of the selection are also passed (``'color'`` and ``'alpha'`` in the ``subsets`` dictionary). Then, ``set_canvas`` gets called after subset updates.

Once we merge this, you can try and see if you can modify ``set_canvas`` to highlight the subsets! :)

@ankurankan Actually bug was there because when the first time call was being made
```python
        if start_state is None and self.state is None:
            self.state = self.random_state()
        elif start_state is not None:
            self.set_start_state(start_state)
```
both `start_state` and `self.state` were None but next time only `start_state` was None, and which was being set as `self.state`

I was able to recreate this problem a couple times locally today, but I wasn't able to track down the interleaving of events that caused the issue. With that said, I believe this is a simple fix to the problem.

In `ACMEServerMixin`, [self.timeout](https://docs.python.org/2/library/socketserver.html#SocketServer.BaseServer.timeout) gives us away to have `handle_request` return after `self.timeout` seconds if it has not received a request. If `shutdown2` has not been called, `handle_request` will be called again, but this allows the code to break out of the `handle_request` function and to check the value of `self._stopped`.

@kuba, I defer to you here as you know more about this code than I do, but I believe this is a trivial fix to the problem.

This is initial work towards fixing the github authorization flow. I think adding 'authenticated' to the app record is a good idea. Initially my thought was to go with a function in src/main/menu called publishAuth:
```javascript
export function githubAuth(item, focusedWindow) {
  const win = new BrowserWindow({ show: false,
                                  webPreferences: { zoomFactor: 0.75 } });
  win.webContents.on('dom-ready', () => {
    if (win.getURL().indexOf('callback?code=') !== -1) {
      win.webContents.executeJavaScript(`
        require('electron').ipcRenderer.send('auth', document.body.textContent);
        `);
      ipc.on('auth', (event, auth) => {
        const authorization = JSON.parse(auth);
        send(focusedWindow, 'menu:publish:auth', authorization.access_token);
        win.close();
        return;
      });
    } else {
      win.show();
    }
  });
  win.loadURL('https://nteract-oauth.now.sh/github');
}
```

and:
```javascript
publishAuthAndGist(){
   publishAuth();
   createSender('menu:publish:gist');
}
```
but theres some issue with synchronicity. Gonna pair with @captainsafia on this right now.
